{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778348490,"nonce":"QBV/ZYRzIrbFYiyvjcte4W6oWfY=","title":"Symlink _artifacts/ children into results/ for unified local navigation","message":"The dual-tree split (`results/` tracked = specs + narratives; `_artifacts/` gitignored = bulk outputs) works for git but creates daily navigation friction. Locally, the spec for a figure is in `results/\u003cexp\u003e/figures/\u003cfig\u003e/spec.json` and the actual `figure.html` is in `_artifacts/\u003cexp\u003e/figures/\u003cfig\u003e/figure.html` — having to switch between two parallel trees to look at one figure is annoying.\n\n**Proposal**: symlink each `_artifacts/\u003cexp\u003e/\u003ctopic\u003e/` child into the corresponding `results/\u003cexp\u003e/\u003ctopic\u003e/` directory. Then `results/\u003cexp\u003e/figures/\u003cfig\u003e/figure.html` exists locally as a symlink resolving to `_artifacts/.../figure.html`, and the user navigates one tree.\n\n**Mechanics**:\n- The symlinks themselves are tiny (path indirection) and could be tracked — git stores the link target string, not the resolved file content.\n- On a fresh clone the symlinks would dangle (pointing to a `_artifacts/` path that does not yet exist); regenerating the artifact restores them. The dangling symlink is informative (\"there is supposed to be an artifact here\").\n- Alternatively: the symlinks could be local-only (gitignored). Tradeoff: tracked = signal that an artifact is expected; gitignored = clean main on fresh clone.\n\n**Caveats**:\n- Need to define a precise rule for which `_artifacts/` paths get symlinked from `results/` (every directory? only files? specific filenames?).\n- Risk: an agent that does not understand the symlink convention could write to the symlink target accidentally and corrupt the dual-tree separation.\n- Existing prior work in this area: a worktree directory `worktrees/feature__structure-migration-mirror-tree/` is still present (likely abandoned), suggesting an earlier attempt at this. Pull lessons learned from that branch (or close it as superseded by this proposal) before reimplementing.\n- Related: `f485c26` (broader results/ folder hierarchy reorganization) — this proposal addresses one specific pain point but not the hierarchy-depth or cloud-provider-subdirs concerns.\n\n**Decision criterion**: this is worth doing if the navigation friction outweighs the implementation + agent-education cost. Likely yes given how often the user says \"where is X\" about figures.\n\nSurfaced from work in `_artifacts/part2_5/runpod/anti_anticipation_loss_shape_6cell/` (pre-reg `2bc95fd`).","files":null}]}